Requirements
============

Amiga OS 2.0 or greater
Triton.library ( included )

@ENDNODE
@NODE "INTRODUCTION" "Introduction"
@NEXT "DEVELOMENT"
@PREV "REQUIREMENTS"
@TOC "MAIN"

Introduction
============

HandBook gives you quick access to all your docs, guides, etc. You
never have to be frustrated about the lack of on-line help again.

Once setup with a viewer, directories and a filename pattern, HandBook
displays all the files that match in a list box. Just pick any file
you want and it opens using your selected program.

The main window will attempt to open on the front-most screen if it is
a Public Screen, otherwise it opens on Workbench. If the viewer
supports it, the file is also opened on the front-most screen.

HandBook also puts an entry in the Tools menu ( in case you forget the
hotkey :) and implements a basic ARexx interface.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "DEVELOMENT" "Development"
@NEXT "INSTALLATION"
@PREV "INTRODUCTION"
@TOC "MAIN"

Development
===========

I chose Triton to implement the GUI for HandBook. This is a small, but
powerful GUI system. The windows are resizable and font-sensitive. The
buttons even have popup help.

If you want the full user distribution of Triton, you can find it on
Aminet in the dev/gui directory. The archive is called Tri14usr.lha.
If you want the developer archive, it lives in the same place and is
called Tri14dev.lha. Alternatively, go to the Triton web site at:

@{I}http://home.pages.de/~szeiger/triton.html@{UI}


I wrote HandBook in Blitz Basic 2.1 using the Blitz Support Suite and
the Blitz Triton conversion. The source code is either included with
this program, or available from my @{"Blitz web-site" LINK "ABOUT"} if you downloaded
from Aminet. The source code could be useful for anyone wanting to
know how to do any of the things HandBook does. I went to a lot of
effort to make sure HandBook did things 'properly', so the source code
is a good reference point.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "INSTALLATION" "Installation"
@NEXT "USAGE"
@PREV "DEVELOMENT"
@TOC "MAIN"

Installation
============

The first thing to do is make sure you have Triton installed. If you
don't already have version 1.4 or higher, the basic Triton library is
included. You must install this first by going to the Triton directory
and running the installer there.

Once you have Triton installed, run the HandBook install program and
follow the instructions.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "CONFIGURATION" "Configuration"
@NEXT "USAGE"
@PREV "INSTALLATION"
@TOC "MAIN"

Configuration
=============

There are two places to configure HandBook. The tooltypes define the
Commodity properties and HandBook.prefs defines the program, paths and
pattern to use.


@{B}Tooltypes@{UB}

    DONOTWAIT
    If you put HandBook in your WBStartup drawer, you must have this
    in the tooltypes

    CX_POPUP=YES/NO
    Determines whether the main window should open when starting.
    Defaults to YES if a value cannot be found.

    CX_POPKEY=<hotkey definition>
    Defines the hotkey to use to open the HandBook window. Defaults to
    alt help if a value cannot be found.

    CX_PRIORITY=<a number between -128 and 127>
    This value is used by Workbench to determine which order to load
    programs in the WBStartup drawer. The higher the number, the
    higher the priority.

    WINLINES=<a number>
    This value determines the minimum ( and therefore the default )
    number of lines to show in the list view. This defaults to 10.

    WINWIDTH=<a number>
    This is the minimum  and therefore the default ) width of the list
    view. The width is given in characters and defaults to 50.

    SHOWDIRS=YES/NO
    This determines how to display the files in the list view. If no,
    only the file name is shown along with the comment for file. If
    yes, the full path of each file is shown, but the comment is not
    shown. The default is NO.


@{B}HandBook.prefs@{UB}

    This file lives in ENVARC: and contains three lines of text. The
    first is the program command line, the second the path(s) to
    search for files and the third is a standard pattern to apply to
    the files.


    The program command line can have a control character of %p which
    is replaced by the name of the public screen HandBook is open on.
    For example, if HandBook was open on the workbench screen:

        SYS:Utilities/Multiview PUBSCREEN=%p

    would be changed to:

        SYS:Utilities/Multiview PUBSCREEN="Workbench"

    The default value for the command line is:

        SYS:Utilities/Multiview PUBSCREEN=%p


    The path definition list the directories HandBook is the search
    for files. A * is used to delimit the paths. For example:

        HELP:*SYS:Utilities/Docs/

    This defines two directories, HELP: and SYS:Utilities/Docs.

    The default path definition is:

        HELP:*SYS:Tools/


    The pattern is a standard DOS pattern to restrict what files
    appear in the main window list. The default is:

        (#?.guide|#?.doc|#?.txt)


    The program, paths and pattern can all be changed in the main
    program. The Setup menu has three options called Change Directory,
    Change Path and Change Pattern. These allow you to define new
    values. Use the Save Settings option in the Project menu to save
    these new values to the HandBook.prefs file.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "USAGE" "Usage"
@NEXT "MENUS"
@PREV "CONFIGURATION"
@TOC "MAIN"

Usage
=====

HandBook is a commodity and can be controlled through Exchange in the
normal way. The main window will always attempt to open on the
front-most screen. If the screen is not a Public Screen, however, it
opens on Workbench.

The defined hotkey can be used to bring up the HandBook window. The
hotkey also closes the window if it is already open. This enables you
to open the window on another screen without having to go and find
where the main window is open. Just push the hotkey twice and the main
window will close and then reopen on the front-most screen.

A new item is also added to the Workbench Tools menu which will bring
the main window up ( in case you forget the hotkey ).


The main window consist of a list of the files found in the specified
directories that match the given pattern. How the files are displayed
depends on the SHOWDIRS option. If SHOWDIRS is NO, the file name along
with any comment attached to that file is shown. If YES, the full path
of the file is shown, but without any comment.

You can open the files by double clicking, or selecting one and
pushing the Open button. This will run the selected program with the
file selected.

The Hide button closes the main window, but leaves HandBook active.
The Quit button closes HandBook.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "MENUS" "Menus"
@NEXT "AREXX"
@PREV "USAGE"
@TOC "MAIN"

Menus
=====

@{B}Project@{UB}
    Refresh        Recreates the list of files in the list box.

    Save Settings  Saves the current setup.

    About          Shows the about box.

    Hide           Hides the main window.

    Quit           Closes HandBook.


@{B}Edit@{UB}
    Rename   Enables you to rename the selected file.

    Comment  Allows you to edit the selected file's comment.
             ( not shown if the full path option is on )


@{B}Setup@{UB}
    Change Directory  Changes the paths used to find files.

    Change Program    Changes the program used to view the files.

    Change Pattern    Changes the pattern to filter the files.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "AREXX" "ARexx Port"
@NEXT "VERSION"
@PREV "MENUS"
@TOC "MAIN"

ARexx Port
==========

HandBook also implements an ARexx interface. The port is called:

@{B}HANDBOOK.1@{UB}

The following commands are accepted:

QUIT
Closes HandBook.

HIDE
Hides the main window if it is open.

DEACTIVATE
Disables the commodity part of HandBook.

SHOW
Shows the main window on the front-most Public Screen or Workbench.

ACTIVATE
Enables the commodity part of HandBook.

INFO
Returns a standard version string for HandBook.

@ENDNODE
